  • Save up to 26% per year on heating and cooling costs. ENERGY STAR certified. Automatically adjusts the temperature when you’re away to never heat or cool an empty home. Compared to a hold of 72°F.
  • Enjoy comfort without compromise. Smart Thermostat Enhanced preheats or precools your home before you arrive, so it’s the perfect temperature the moment you walk in. Automatically adjusts to your desired temperature when you’re home or sleeping to keep you comfortable day and night. Adjusts the temperature to account for humidity so your home always feels like the temperature you’ve set.
  • Easy to install and use every day, ecobee Smart Thermostat Enhanced comes with everything you need for installation. Most people install it themselves in about 45 minutes or less. Use your smart home platform and the ecobee app to control your thermostat from anywhere with your smartphone, tablet, or Apple Watch.
  • ecobee Smart Thermostat Enhanced is made with quality materials and designed to last on your wall for over a decade. It’s hardwired so you never have to worry about losing control or replacing batteries. If you run into problems, our dedicated support team is available 7 days a week.
  • Add in a SmartSensor which allows you to measure the temperature in rooms that matter most, like the nursery or bedroom. It reads temperature and movement in whatever room it is placed in for complete home monitoring and energy savings (SmartSensor sold separately).
  • Compatible with most 24VAC HVAC systems: furnaces, ACs (2H/2C), heat pumps (2H/2C + 2 stage AUX), boilers, PTACs, and fan coil units (3 fan speeds). Includes Power Extender Kit for C-Wire-less homes, ensuring easy installation. Dual-band Wi-Fi: 802.11 b/g/n @ 2.4GHz, 802.11 a/n/ac @ 5GHz

Additional details

The all new ecobee's Smart Thermostat Enhanced gives you automatic energy savings and adapts to your lifestyle by adjusting temperature based on occupancy, suggesting schedule changes, and optimizing your energy savings. eco+ comes with features that automatically turn temperatures down when you're away or asleep. Works with your smart device or Apple Watch and connects to your smart home system like Apple HomeKit, Amazon Alexa, Google Assistant, SmartThings, and IFTTT. Trusted by experts and made for the planet, Smart Thermostat Enhanced delivers unparalleled comfort and savings.

    • RickyPetite
      5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      What a difference a smart thermostat makes
      Reviewed in the United States on January 24, 2024
      Style: Thermostat
      I upgraded from an ancient Honeywell dumb thermostat (only displayed Celsius). Wow, what a difference. I added 2 sensors since the thermostat is in a less traveled room. Set-up couldn't have been easier (very Apple-esque). The sensors report patterns of habitation... See more
      I upgraded from an ancient Honeywell dumb thermostat (only displayed Celsius). Wow, what a difference. I added 2 sensors since the thermostat is in a less traveled room. Set-up couldn't have been easier (very Apple-esque). The sensors report patterns of habitation and adjust the temp accordingly. The main unit looks great, very modern and sleek. iOS app is excellent as is the web portal.

      Installation tip (DIY'er, use at your own risk): I have a simple single stage AC, furnace. On the furnace, locate the control board. Focus on the wires that come from the thermostat (usually 4 wires - R, W, Y, G). If you are lucky, there will be 5 wires (one plugged into the C terminal - common). Ignore any other wires (I had 2, R and W which came from the AC unit and shared connections on the furnace board). Look for any extra wires which are part of the thermostat bundle that are unused (if you don't already have a common wire connected). The thermostat wire is a lot like a Cat 5 wire with multiple sub-wires of various colors, some unused). Pick one that is unused at the furnace and unused at the thermostat. Plug it into the common "C" port on the furnace and then into the C port on the thermostat. Instant "common" connection (this powers the unit rather than relying on batteries). Plug in the rest of the wires on the thermostat as directed by instructions on the ecobee site (usually straightforward, red to red etc). Done! If you don't have a common or any other unused wires in the bundle, you will need to use the adapter that comes with the thermostat. Also pretty straightforward (the adapter pulls power from the common connection and feeds it to the thermostat from the other, non-common wires). Very pleased. Great system.

      My 12-yr-old thermostat finally gave out and I wanted to get another of the same. My local HVAC company no longer carries this brand. There are no other suppliers within 100 miles of me. I contacted the thermostat company but they don't sell online or direct to public.... See more
      My 12-yr-old thermostat finally gave out and I wanted to get another of the same. My local HVAC company no longer carries this brand. There are no other suppliers within 100 miles of me. I contacted the thermostat company but they don't sell online or direct to public. I not only like this thermostat for the many options it has, but I like that it has subscription-free remote access via a nice app and also their website.

      So, I bought the Ecobee Enhanced. I have simple wiring so install was very quick. The Ecobee app and the webpage are good for remote control. I am not using the two occupancy sensors just yet. In fact, I have dumbed down everything on the Ecobee and it is just on heating hold mode with one temperature right now. As a dumb thermostat it's working fine. I don't have a need for all the programming options right now but am eager to see how they compare to my old thermostat when I do. The old unit was the bomb.

      I give the Ecobee four stars instead of five for a couple of minor reasons:

      1) My thermostat is in a narrow hallway. I liked walking by my old thermostat and seeing the standby screen with weather, indoor temp, and time. If I wanted to adjust it, I just needed to touch the screen first to 'wake it up'. The Ecobee has a similar standby screen, but it's not possible for me to see it LOL As soon as the Ecobee 'senses' someone coming near it switches the display. This is a big complaint from others as well. There is even a Reddit thread, "Sneaking up on my Ecobee..." LOL I do wish the company would make leaving the standby screen on display as an option. 99 times out of 100 I'm just walking by and not going to adjust anything.

      2) The Ecobee website does not offer the option to leave me logged in so I can quickly access the thermostat's settings. Many websites ask, on a private device, to remember for some period like 30 days. My old thermostat's webpage was that way. Not Ecobee's, I have to login every time no matter how many times a day I access it. I also cannot bookmark the exact settings page I want like I could with my old thermostat, always have to enter from the main screen.

      If/when I start using programmed modes again this will be a lot more painful. I am on my computer all day long so it's easier for me to bookmark and hop to a webpage quickly for everything I do. I really don't want to have to pull out my phone and call up an app. Not the end of the world, but website could be a lot more friendly.

      I have previously owned 2 different generations of Nest thermostat. They are easy to use and do a good job. But I wanted to upgrade to Ecobee because the logic is more advanced. Installation was very easy for me (having done it many times before). But I found that there... See more
      I have previously owned 2 different generations of Nest thermostat. They are easy to use and do a good job. But I wanted to upgrade to Ecobee because the logic is more advanced. Installation was very easy for me (having done it many times before). But I found that there were no real installation instructions included with this thermostat. It had stickers to label the wires but it didn't tell you what to do when your wires didn't have a corresponding post to connect to the thermostat base. I have an RC/RH red wire but there is only an R port on the base. I had to google search to find out what to do. It also came with a special wiring harness with little to no instructions on what it was for. Again, google search to find it is only intended for people with certain wiring designs. Ecobee could do a much better job in their instructions. There are some software design parts that I do not like such as defining a schedule each day. Nest was easy...just insert the temp you want at the time you want each day and save. Ecobee complicates it by having Home, Away etc and it adds unnecessary extra steps to plot out my daily/weekly schedule. I found that annoying. But it adds in things like historical detailed data including outdoor temps and you can see graphs and other long term details. As a nerd, I like this data.

      I have nothing but rave reviews for this thing. I'd give it 10 stars if I could. Installation was super easy, with the App guiding me through everything from mounting to wiring. When I discovered 2 wires which more or less appeared to do the same thing, I reached out to their support group via phone. The queue was busy, but it allowed me to request a call back without losing my place in line (I love that BTW). When the agent called me back, she wasn't exactly sure of the right answer, so she sent me an email which allowed me to reply with pictures of both the thermostat wiring and furnace wiring. She then consulted with in-house experts and provided me with the correct answer (which I had correctly guessed, but was nice to have expert confirmation).

      Anyway, on the 3rd day I received a text message from my Ecobee telling me that my heat pump Aux Heat (electric heating strips) had been running for over 3 hours(!) It hasn't been cold enough for that to be necessary, so I called an HVAC guy and he found that my freon (or whatever they call it today) was low by about 2 lbs, which meant I had a leak somewhere. He recharged the system, found that 2 or 3 valves were leaking (used soapy water) and replaced them. $200 and all was operating nominally. Awesome. I could have spent that in electric alone if the unit continued using the hyper expensive Aux Heat strips. I probably wouldn't have known for weeks or months if it hadn't sent me that text. And the alert itself was something it was pre-programmed to monitor - I never set that up!

      Did I mention how nice it looks on my wall? I used the wall plate to cover the screw holes from the old one, painted it to match the wall, and it's Gorgeous. It also shows humidity levels, along with a single tap for daily and 4-day weather forecasts. I used to have Nest thermostats at my old house, but I wanted something compatible with Apple HomeKit, so went with Ecobee. No regrets. Nest never again for me.
